Dianea ſuffered not theſe words without diſpleaſure: Yet ſhe was unwilling that any externall ſignes ſhould appeare to her Father, deſiring no
   •
 to oppoſe her Diſcontents though very reaſonable. For a while ſhe deferred her Anſwer, as if ſhe premeditated words, or rather becauſe ſhee was to declare an Opinion remote from that of her Father, ſhe was willing to prolong as much as was poſſible her angring him. Laſtly, the Enſignes, I know not whether of Shame or Diſcontent, unfolded in her Countenance, ſhee thus anſwered him;
